item.title: The private server progression
item.dc:creator: @k0_twin k0 twin
item.description:
@k0_twin wrote:

CoonHunter:

Only reason I got into it was because of 2 things. I wanted to learn some programming to feel smart (man was I wrong about feeling smart, the more i learn, the stupider i feel). As well as the fact my fav server had shut down due to a computer failure. Talked to owner of it on MSN, and he pointed me to a base + client. Have to say, its one of the funnest things I have done, by the time I was done I had created about 4-5 custom minigames. (almost rabled on and gave out the one that got my 40-50 regular players, stopped myself :P)

That’s funny, that’s exactly what happened to me. I had a server I loved and played everyday where I found a small group of “friends”. When the server shut down we all wanted to keep playing so I found a copy of the source and learned how to run it.

From there, about 3-4 years ago, I found that I had a passion from programming, and now I’m about to head off to college to get a degree in computer science.

item.title: The private server progression
item.dc:creator: @CoonHunter CoonHunter
item.description:
@CoonHunter wrote:

Mr. Bobby:

It seems like rsps are being passed on and on with more and more poorly written code and just straight up useless methods. on top of that to many download and run sources are being released to a community of people who haven’t bothered to look into the server’s classes besides to change there server’s name. If only blank sources were released in the dl sections across all the rsps communities and the tutorial section wasn’t just spammed with “find this and under it add this” tutorials 80% of the servers on the status lists wouldn’t exist and only people who know what there doing would own servers.

Thus the reason I taught myself 99% of what I know. Too many people these days look for the easy way out, and don’t try to put effort into it. If it was up to me I would just lock the tutorials board and make it so you had to send it to a certain email, mods looked it over and if they liked it, posted it with creds to you. Mods doing this on their own free will, and not being a requirement.

Read full topic
